A lament on the death of Quintilius Varus, the common friend of Horace and of Vergil. 'He was an accomplished and, according to Horace's words, Epist. ἑ, 3, 438 ff, an impartial critic, whose judgment was valued by his literary friends, Quintillo siquid recitares, ‘corsus &odes ξ lme' aiebat ‘el hoc? melius sc posse negares, 1 bis terque eaper- sum frastra, delere jubebat Ι et male tornatas incudi reddere versu.» The year of his death is fixed by St. Jerome's entry against 24 Bc Quintilius Cremonensis Vergy'lz' et Horati familiaris morilur. This ode must have been written within the next few months. The Varus, of the eighteenth ode is probably identical with Quintilius. Metre, 72.
